@node INTRO "Introduction"

DUD is a programm in the @{B}D@{UB}ir@{B}u@{UB}sage category, you can let it
measure how much place a directory occupies on a volume. Contrary to most
other dus, you can use DUD with your mouse and from the workbench.

DUD has been designed for usage with OFS/FFS. By using it with other
filesystems DUD may give incorrect results and show misbehaviour.

@endnode


@node SYSTEM "System requirements"
Your Amiga should fulfil the following technical requirements:

 - AmigaOS 3.0 or better

 - MUI 3.0 or better


As DUD is not loading single files but scanning directories, a fast cpu
will be very advantageous next to a fast harddisk.

@endnode



@node INSTALLATION "(De-)Installation"
@{U}Installation:@{UU}

To install DUD you can simply drag its icon into a drawer on the workbench.
You can choose between a version that runs on all Amigas (DUD_68000) or a
version that needs an MC68020 or better (DUD_68020). The 68020 has disabled
some special error checking like stack checking, which is not needed under
normal circumstances, so it can run at maximum speed.


DUD┤s settings will be created automatically in @{B}ENVARC:mui@{UB} and are
usually called @{B}DUD.1.cfg@{UB} and @{B}DUD.1.wini@{UB}. If you use the
cache option then there will be some other files created on you harddisk,
but you can choose the directory for them freely.


@{U}Deinstallation:@{UU}

Provided you ever (never) want to remove DUD from your system, you will have
to delete the mentiond files by hand.
If you have not chosen a special directory for the cache files, they will have
been created in the same directory as DUD. Their name consists of the prefix
@{B}DUD_@{UB} + the name of the volume without the @{B}:@{UB} + the Suffix
@{B}.dat@{UB}. So, the name of the cache file for Workbench would be
@{B}DUD_Workbench.dat@{UB}.

@endnode


@node EXAMPLE "Example"
You may start DUD form the workbench with a doubleclick on its icon. The main
window will present you a list of volumes and you may choose one of them (for
testing you should choose a partition with not too many entries in it, as
reading them all can take a few minutes). DUD will start reading the whole
directory structure of the volume. After that the top level directories will
be presented in a list on the right side and as a diagram on the left side
of the window. You may notice the entry @{B}""@{UB}, which represents the
current directory.


The list offers you three types of information

1) Name of the directory: it represents always a subdirectory to the current
directory

2) Percentage: it shows you, how much of place, that the current directory
with all of its subdirectories uses is used by this directory and all its
subdirectories. The percentage is always relative to the current directory.
The directory @{B}""@{UB} stands for the usage of the files in the current
directory.

3) Value: Gives you always the number of either bytes or blocks that the
directory and all of its subdirectories use.

The title has correspondending values for the current directory, only the
percentage is always relative to the volume.


You may now select one of the directories with a doubleclick. All of its
subdirectories will be shown and the selected directory will get the
current directory. As the whole disk structure has been read already
no further disk access is necessary. You may also select a subdirectory
in the diagram on the left side.


If you want to go back to the parent directory, you should select @{B}Parent@{UB}
 right under the list. The @{B}Root@{UB} gadget will bring you to the top level
directory.


You may sort the list either by name or by size with the lowest cycle
gadget.


Just above you will find two other cycle gadgets. The right allows you to
view either blocks or bytes in the list. The left orders the columns.
Just try it out.


Pressing the @{B}Check@{UB} gadget will read the directory and all of its
subdirectories again, but only if they have changed. @{B}CheckAll@{UB} will
do the same for the whole volume. These two operations will be much faster
than reading a whole disk for the first time.


You can change the look of the diagram in the settings menu.
Try @{B}Settings->Drawing Style@{UB}.


For a faster scannng of the whole volume next time, you should save the disk
structure with @{B}Projekt->Save@{B}@{UB}.


For reading a new volume press the @{B}New Volume@{UB} gadget.


Do not forget to save you settings with @{B}Settings->Save Settings@{UB} before
you quit the program.

@endnode



@node PMENU "Projekt menu"
@{B}New Volume@{UB} will show you the volume list again. The dir structure of
the old volume will get lost.


@{B}Save@{UB} saves the disk structure of the current volume in a file.
This file works like a cache for the disk structure, so next reading will be
considerably faster.


@{B}Save In...@{UB} lets you choose the directory, in which the cache files
will be saved. Predefined is the same directory DUD has been started from.


@{B}About...@{UB} gives useless information.


@{B}About MUI...@{UB} gives USEFUL information about MUI.


@{B}Quit Program@{UB} quits DUD.

@endnode



@node -MENU "Dog menu"
@{B}Disk Info@{UB} gives some additional informations about the current volume.
@{B}Device@{UB} informs you about the device name, @{B}FileSystem@{UB} about
the name of the filesystem. @{B}Total Blocks@{UB} is the maximum number of blocks
that can be used on the volume, @{B}Used Blocks@{UB} means, how many blocks are
used already. @{B}Blocksize@{UB} gives the number of bytes in a block and
@{B}Datablocksize@{UB} gives the number of databytes in a block. The second
@{B}Used Blocks@{UB} value informs you about the number of blocks calculated by DUD.
@{B}Bitmap Blocks@{UB}, @{B}Directories@{UB} and @{B}Files@{UB} hold the number of
bitmap blocks, directories and files. @{B}Oldest Directory@{UB} shows you the oldest
directory on your disk. @{B}LastOpTime@{UB} informs ayou about the time spent during
the last operation of DUD


The @{B}Parent@{UB}, @{B}Root@{UB}, @{B}Check@{UB} and @{B}CheckAll@{UB} menus
have the same functions as the correspondending gadgets.

@{B}@{UB}
@endnode



@node SMENU "Settings menu"
@{B}AutoCheck@{UB} triggers the same action as if you pressed Check/Check All.
@{B}Load@{UB} does so after the reading of a cache file, @{B}DirChange@{UB} does
so after every change of the current directory.


@{B}AutoSave@{UB} makes a cache file as if you selected @{B}Project->Save@{UB}.
@{B}Quit@{UB} saves the disk structure just before quitting DUD, @{B}Volume Change@{UB}
 does it when you select a new volume.


@{B}Use Cachefile@{UB} selects whether cache files are used or not.


@{B}Use XPK@{UB} denotes, if you want to pack the cache files with XPK. You cannot
select this menu if XPK could not be found on your system. If you do use it,
then the cache file will be saved first to T: and then copied in compressed
form to the original directory for your cache files. XPK will save some space
on your hd, but loading and saving will take a little bit longer.
Two examples:
(Time was measured on a 68030/25MHz system)

                |       uncompressed       |    XPK-NUKE compressed

                |  Load  |  Save  |    Size|  Load  |  Save  |  Size

----------------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|------------

Meeting-Pearls 3|    6.1s|    4.9s|278.022B|    8.4s|   17.9s|95.664B

8004 Dirs, 650MB|        |        |        |        |        |

----------------|--------|--------|--------|--------|--------|------------

HD-Partition    |    0.6s|    0.6s| 24.521B|    1.0s|    2.1s|11.308B

719 Dirs, 80MB  |



@{B}Check Links@{UB} selects, if Links should be scanned, too. You do not
want to set this option in general, because it can give you wrong results.


@{B}Special RAM@{UB} will use a special method for scanning the "Ram Disk:",
because it does not organize its data in a documented way like OFS/FFS. This
method is built on the programmers exploration into the deep AmigaOS3.1
"Ram Disk:" jungle, so it may fail with other versions of the "Ram Disk:" and
that is the reason why you can deselect this menu. After changing the state of
this menu you should let DUD scan the "Ram Disk:" once more (drag the icon
onto DUD┤s window).


@{B}Change AMICDROM BlockSize@{UB} solves a problem with the AmiCDROM-FS. For
some strange reason AmiCDROM gives a BlockSize of 8192Bytes, but this will
lead DUD to wrong results. Turn this option on and DUD will internally set
BlockSize to DataBlockSize.


@{B}DCxFS@{UB} selects the treatment of the special DCOFS/DCFFS blocks.
@{B}Approximate@{UB} gives only an approximation (error under 1%), @{B}Low Level@{UB}
 gives exact reults, but takes longer time and can lead to compatibility problems.


@{B}Show@{UB} hides the diagram (@{B}Diagram@{UB}) or the
list (@{B}List@{UB}).


@{B}Drawing Style@{UB} changes the style of the diagram. @{B}Pattern@{UB} draws
patterns, @{B}Outline@{UB} draws outlines and @{B}Colour@{UB} (surprise!)
coulours.


@{B}Save Settings@{UB} will save all settings in ENVARC:. Beside the entries of
the settings menu, the selections of the four cycle gadgets and the directory
for the cache files will be saved.

@endnode



@node GADGETS "Gadgets"
@{B}Parent@{UB} shows you the parent directory.


@{B}Root@{UB} shows you the top level directory.


@{B}Check@{UB} reads the current directory and all of its subdirectories again.


@{B}CheckAll@{UB} reads the whole disk structure again.


@{B}N % B@{UB} arranges the columns in the list.


@{B}Bytes@{UB}|@{B}Blocks@{UB} gives values in either bytes or blocks.
In the list @{B}B@{UB} represents single bytes/blocks, @{B}K@{UB} represents
1024 bytes/1000 blocks, @{B}M@{UB} represents 2^20 bytes/10^6 blocks, @{B}G@{UB}
 represents 2^30 bytes/10^9 blocks.


@{B}Alpha@{UB}|@{B}Size@{UB} lets you choose the criterion for
sorting the subdirectories.


@{B}B@{UB}|@{B}B/K/M/G@{UB} yumyum.

@endnode



@node BUGS "Known bugs and problems"
DUD has been programmed to work with OFS/FFS formatted volumes. By using it
with other filesystems you can get incorrect results.
@{LINDENT 3}

RAM-Disk: The RAM-disk does not really work with blocks, so DUD has a special
routine for the RAM: that comes with AmigaOS3.1. DUD might give wrong results
with other versions of AmigaOS.


AmiCDROM (CDROM-Handler 1.15, PD):
The correctnes of the block value differs from CD to CD, great detailed
analysis of 7 CDs shows incorrect results of in a range under 1%, but the error
can be higher if it contains audio tracks. In addition you should set the
SD-value higher than the default of 5. A value of 50 enables DUD to scan disk
up to three times faster than before (other programs will like that, too).


CDFileSystem (comes with AmigaOS 3.1): Contrary to AmiCDROM the
Buffers are not so important as with AmiCDROM, but can speedup things, too.
Results are somewhat incorrect, too.


No other filesystems tested.
@{LINDENT 0}


My english is not very good, do not feel offended in any way, if you find any
bugs in this documentation, please. MAIL ME CORRECTIONS!


DUD can only display volumes up to 2GByte. If a volumes has more data, then
DUD will switch from byte to block display. Internally DUD only handles blocks,
so you might expect DUD to handle volumes with 1024GByte or more.


Notify is not working right now.


DUD uses the stack very intensive, the predefinded stack (30000) is big enough
for more than 700 directory levels (The whole number of directories is only
limited by ram).


The saving/loading of cache files might be somewhat slow on AmigaOS 3.0.
Better use AmigaOS 3.1+


DUD has not seen many beta testers, there might be some other bugs left.


@endnode



